Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – As in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on all tongues, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's about the environment and the climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a driving role in the Paris Agreement negotiations, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
However, despite their importance, these measures are not enough to meet the challenges facing the world today.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying off, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And victims of respiratory diseases are becoming more numerous as air pollution worsens.
We have, however, reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's see these people, more numerous each day, ready to take action to question their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also taking action, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it's the policies and politicians, at the national as well as European level, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let's make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no choice: the EU's net emissions of carbon dioxide must be reduced to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can massively invest in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transport, as well as maritime and air commercial transport.
And, by closely working with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a true circular economy, efficient in waste.
Each year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are converted into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work right now, for example, by launching a European initiative to fight planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by abolishing plastics in our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, the populations of wild species have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations Conference on Biodiversity, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put a bold plan on the table for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them !) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to accompany this green transition.
But these massive tasks that await us, we will not be able to accomplish if it is still the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear the costs.
All the measures envisaged must therefore be designed above all to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must work with our partners today to international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it serves no purpose to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the new EU political cycle.
Because we are in a state of acute ecological debt, and it would be more than justified that the stability and growth pact that applies to the public finances of member states finds an equivalent for the green objectives of Europe!
To achieve its objectives, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not be afraid to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market, could significantly stimulate innovation for the environment.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros of investments each year to meet the commitments made under the Paris Agreement.
This is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral climate-focused funding provider.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, making the most of private sector investments, could still further reinforce the Union's power of action.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: thanks to the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what the Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon".
Finally, although some member states will see this as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, as well as on subsidies for fossil fuels. In short, on integrating sustainability into public spending.
Behind these projects, this key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must define ambitious objectives and "missions" with short-term and long-term relevance that have real social resonance.
With the member states and the European Parliament, we will have to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to escape the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal". But it is not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
